{
  "doc_id": "3622",
  "text": "Due to the excellent ion exchange ability and high surface area, natural zeolites [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and synthetic zeolites [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] are employed to remove the ammoniacal nitrogen from aqueous solution by the ion exchange method. Karadag et al. [CITATION_5] and Huang et al. [CITATION_6] demonstrated that both the natural Turkish clinoptilolite and Chinese zeolite had strong ability to remove 2 Journal of Chemistry ammonium from aqueous solutions. In recent years, many researchers have investigated ammoniacal nitrogen removal from aqueous solutions by using eco-friendly material, such as the zeolites derived from agricultural waste, fly ash, or industrial waste. For example, Yusof et al. [CITATION_7] reported that zeolite Y synthesized from rice husk ash waste was found to have higher adsorption capacity than mordenite for ammonium removal, and the equilibrium isotherm proved its monolayer adsorption. Mishra and Tiwari [CITATION_8] found that zeolite 13X originated from Indian fly ash had a good sorption property for metal ions at acidic pH. However, the collection and processing of these raw materials are the major engineering problems to be solved in the case of commercializing those waste-originated zeolites.",
